WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.090 --> 00:00:04.070
FEMALE SPEAKER: Today in
partnership with Zagat

00:00:04.070 --> 00:00:06.650
we are privileged to
have Hugh Acheson.

00:00:06.650 --> 00:00:08.500
Hugh Acheson is the
chef and partner

00:00:08.500 --> 00:00:13.280
of four restaurants in Georgia,
5 &amp; 10, The National, Empire

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:15.310
State South, and The Florence.

00:00:15.310 --> 00:00:19.730
In 2010 Hugh competed on Bravo's
"Top Chef Masters" season

00:00:19.730 --> 00:00:22.500
three, and he returned to
the hit show as a judge

00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:24.380
starting in season nine.

00:00:24.380 --> 00:00:27.700
Hugh won the James Beard
award for Best Chef Southeast

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:31.990
in 2012, and most recently he
released his third cookbook,

00:00:31.990 --> 00:00:34.820
"The Broad Fork" which he'll be
showing us a couple of recipes

00:00:34.820 --> 00:00:36.080
from today.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:38.410
So without further
ado, please join me

00:00:38.410 --> 00:00:39.500
in welcoming Hugh Acheson.

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:40.416
HUGH ACHESON: Bonjour.

00:00:40.416 --> 00:00:45.520
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:47.240
HUGH ACHESON: So, I'm Canadian.

00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:51.920
Hence is my denim on denim look
today, the Canadian tuxedo.

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:55.370
I am wearing khakis though, so
I didn't complete the outfit.

00:00:55.370 --> 00:00:55.870
OK.

00:00:55.870 --> 00:00:57.550
We're going to make two things.

00:00:57.550 --> 00:01:00.370
Now this book is really
meant to be-- it literally

00:01:00.370 --> 00:01:02.880
came about as an answer to
somebody down the street

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:05.400
when I was picking up my
CSA box in Athens, Georgia.

00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:07.720
On this beautiful historic
street we live on,

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:11.360
walk down in a quintessentially
American moment,

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:14.540
you know, with my two daughters,
our hair flowing in the winds

00:01:14.540 --> 00:01:18.540
and we pick up our
CSA box, because it's

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:19.881
supposed to be doing.

00:01:19.881 --> 00:01:22.380
We're supposed to be cooking
from scratch, and its goodness.

00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:25.220
And there was this one
annoying professorial guy,

00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:29.530
because it's a college town
and they lurk on corners.

00:01:29.530 --> 00:01:32.240
And he was like, what the
hell do I do with kohlrabi.

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:34.620
And he'd ask me questions
like this every week

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:38.890
and I was, like, dude, lay off.

00:01:38.890 --> 00:01:43.050
It's just because I'm the mantle
of chefdom in Athens, Georgia.

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:45.000
They come to me and
ask me these questions

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:47.940
and it was ongoing and nonstop.

00:01:47.940 --> 00:01:49.890
But it got me thinking
that nobody actually

00:01:49.890 --> 00:01:52.760
knows what to do with kohlrobi.

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:55.160
And nobody knows what to do
with a lot of vegetables.

00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:58.407
Or as Americans, in our
kitchens, we cook like this.

00:01:58.407 --> 00:02:00.990
We cook the things we know, the
things that our parents taught

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:03.160
us, the things maybe our
grandparents taught us,

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:05.580
the things from our community,
the things from maybe

00:02:05.580 --> 00:02:10.490
our heritage past, and those are
recipes we know and understand.

00:02:10.490 --> 00:02:11.999
And we often don't
break them down,

00:02:11.999 --> 00:02:13.790
even though we're
surrounded by great food,

00:02:13.790 --> 00:02:15.998
and you guys eat out all
the time and eat great food.

00:02:15.998 --> 00:02:18.210
Rarely do you go out and
actually try and cook

00:02:18.210 --> 00:02:19.967
something new.

00:02:19.967 --> 00:02:22.300
So it's meant to sort of pull
the blinders off, and just

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:26.112
cook four to five recipes
for one single ingredient.

00:02:26.112 --> 00:02:28.570
So it goes through pretty much
the whole list of everything

00:02:28.570 --> 00:02:32.400
I would have gotten in that
CSA box in a full year.

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:35.760
Some of the things you will not
experience, even in California.

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:38.480
Some of them you will
definitely experience.

00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:42.480
If we were in Wisconsin
it would be different.

00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:43.590
But here we are.

00:02:43.590 --> 00:02:46.650
So first we're going to
do a really simple salad

00:02:46.650 --> 00:02:51.780
with purslane, which
is either-- sometimes

00:02:51.780 --> 00:02:53.610
it's farmed and
sometimes is foraged.

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:56.410
But it looks like this,
and it's a succulent.

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:58.850
And it's kind of got a
nice bitter sourness to it

00:02:58.850 --> 00:03:00.460
as a green.

00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:02.800
And then there's cantaloupe,
and there's prosciutto.

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:05.830
You could use really
good prosciutto de parma,

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:10.515
or you could use whatever fine
deli meats you could find.

00:03:10.515 --> 00:03:12.890
In the salad we're going to
make a vinaigrette with that,

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:15.220
but starting off, we're
going to take a sweet onion.

00:03:15.220 --> 00:03:17.650
And I've peeled
it, but you can see

00:03:17.650 --> 00:03:21.560
that the core part of where
it was attached to the root,

00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:25.157
and then immersed into the
ground and the greens--

00:03:25.157 --> 00:03:27.740
the ground level would be right
here and the greens coming up.

00:03:27.740 --> 00:03:29.750
This is where the
actual root stem was.

00:03:29.750 --> 00:03:33.530
And that's going to keep it
kind of attached as we cut down.

00:03:33.530 --> 00:03:35.180
So I peeled it and
then I'm just going

00:03:35.180 --> 00:03:39.400
to cut down with a
pretty sharp knife,

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:41.850
and kind of keep them
together and that'll just

00:03:41.850 --> 00:03:43.350
aid in the cookery of it.

00:03:43.350 --> 00:03:46.810
So we're going to add a little
bit of butter to the pan.

00:03:46.810 --> 00:03:51.030
This pans on medium
heat, because,

00:03:51.030 --> 00:03:54.220
and I'm going to jack it up
just to sort of medium, medium.

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:58.460
Right now it's four, I'm
going to take it to five.

00:03:58.460 --> 00:04:03.010
Sun does not go up to 11,
which is the "Spinal Tap"

00:04:03.010 --> 00:04:07.930
reference for all of
you over 40 in the room.

00:04:07.930 --> 00:04:10.470
Then we're going to take these,
and just put them in here

00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:13.740
and it's a sensory thing,
it's a flavor thing,

00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:15.930
but it's the best
smell that you'll ever

00:04:15.930 --> 00:04:20.420
have in a kitchen, which is
onions cooking in butter.

00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:23.590
So we're going to continue that,
just with a couple more slices.

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:27.650
Again this is-- you want to
work carefully with a knife,

00:04:27.650 --> 00:04:30.417
but I know this sounds
contrary to logic,

00:04:30.417 --> 00:04:32.250
but you want your knives
to be really sharp,

00:04:32.250 --> 00:04:34.710
because the wound
will be a lot cleaner.

00:04:34.710 --> 00:04:37.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:37.550 --> 00:04:40.810
HUGH ACHESON: So we're going
to process through some melon

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:41.549
as that cooks.

00:04:41.549 --> 00:04:43.840
So what we're going to do,
is we're going to take this,

00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:47.170
we're going to caramelize pretty
deeply, and for lack of time

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:51.314
I'm going to raise this
up seven out of ten.

00:04:51.314 --> 00:04:52.980
Caramelize them pretty
deeply so they've

00:04:52.980 --> 00:04:54.450
got a fair bit of color.

00:04:54.450 --> 00:04:57.270
I'll add seasoning in the
form of a little bit of salt.

00:04:57.270 --> 00:05:00.240
So salt is not a spice,
salt is a flavor extractor.

00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:01.870
It pulls out liquid
from your palate,

00:05:01.870 --> 00:05:04.130
it pulls out flavor
out of food, and you're

00:05:04.130 --> 00:05:06.710
looking for that synergy
and maximization of the two.

00:05:06.710 --> 00:05:09.990
And if you use too
much, it's gross.

00:05:09.990 --> 00:05:12.550
So we're going to
take half of these

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:13.970
and puree them in a blender.

00:05:13.970 --> 00:05:15.440
This is a Vitamix.

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:18.570
It can puree, you
look online and you

00:05:18.570 --> 00:05:22.140
guys can laugh as they
puree apple products on it.

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:24.260
Then the other half
were going to reserve

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:26.280
the beauty of the salad
and it's integrity.

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:28.029
So we'll have beautiful
caramelized onions

00:05:28.029 --> 00:05:29.390
dotting through that.

00:05:29.390 --> 00:05:31.140
But the other half is
going to go in here.

00:05:31.140 --> 00:05:35.050
It's going to get pureed with
some vinegar and some mustard,

00:05:35.050 --> 00:05:36.730
and then mounted
with some olive oil

00:05:36.730 --> 00:05:39.980
to create an
emulsified vinaigrette.

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:44.630
And meanwhile as that goes, let
me just pick this off to side,

00:05:44.630 --> 00:05:46.780
and start on recipe
number two as we go.

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:48.850
I've got an oven under
here, and the oven,

00:05:48.850 --> 00:05:53.650
said oven is at 400 right now.

00:05:53.650 --> 00:05:57.510
I'm going to put this
on seven out of 10.

00:05:57.510 --> 00:06:00.600
And we're going to get
some tomatoes roasting.

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:05.100
These tomatoes-- so you
want to work in seasons,

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:07.320
but if you want to
work with tomatoes

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:10.690
and you're not in the season of
summer, which is tomato season,

00:06:10.690 --> 00:06:12.100
I would buy Roma tomatoes.

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:13.680
Because they're
inherently-- seem

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:17.950
to be the most stable and
consistent tomato out there.

00:06:17.950 --> 00:06:20.562
They're not large
and mealy and weird.

00:06:20.562 --> 00:06:22.770
And they actually can
concentrate their flavor really

00:06:22.770 --> 00:06:25.760
well by doing what we're about
to do, which is roasting them.

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:29.190
So you're going to get rid
of a lot of the superfluous

00:06:29.190 --> 00:06:32.440
liquid in them, in favor of
keeping the sugars behind.

00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:33.940
So I'm just going
to cut off the top

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:35.990
and cut them down
lengthwise, and then we're

00:06:35.990 --> 00:06:38.110
going to get them in
a pan and get them

00:06:38.110 --> 00:06:40.690
slathered with just a
little bit of olive oil,

00:06:40.690 --> 00:06:43.280
and some salt and pepper,
fresh thyme, and garlic.

00:06:46.450 --> 00:06:49.270
This is thyme, right?

00:06:49.270 --> 00:06:52.500
You bought the shaky thing
of thyme six years ago,

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:54.290
you should throw it away.

00:06:54.290 --> 00:06:57.970
Herbs are leafy green things,
spices are barks and seeds.

00:06:57.970 --> 00:07:01.820
They differ a lot, but both are
essential oils-- are contained

00:07:01.820 --> 00:07:03.910
in them that give us
the flavor, but if they

00:07:03.910 --> 00:07:06.302
sit around and dry out, they
don't have as much flavor.

00:07:06.302 --> 00:07:08.260
There are definitely some
uses for dried herbs,

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:11.810
don't get me wrong,
but not many.

00:07:11.810 --> 00:07:13.890
And spices go stale
as well, so you

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:16.160
got excited about taco
night eight years ago,

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:18.580
the cumin is probably--
it's time to move on.

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:21.660
So buy spices in small amounts,
and get rid of them or motor

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:23.490
through them often.

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:25.710
This is a clove
of peeled garlic,

00:07:25.710 --> 00:07:29.120
if you buy pre-minced
garlic, you are dead to me.

00:07:29.120 --> 00:07:31.449
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:31.449 --> 00:07:32.240
HUGH ACHESON: Good.

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:33.440
Moving on.

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:38.190
We're going to discard this,
that's the good garbage.

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:40.640
That's the bad garbage.

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:43.369
I'm going to put just a little
bit of olive oil in the pan,

00:07:43.369 --> 00:07:44.910
and then we're going
to put these in.

00:07:44.910 --> 00:07:48.330
Just skin side u-- or the
cut side up, skin side down,

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:49.970
and then we're
going to season just

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:56.440
with a little bit of
salt. I use kosher salt.

00:07:56.440 --> 00:07:59.057
What kind of kosher salt
is this, diamond crystal?

00:07:59.057 --> 00:07:59.890
FEMALE SPEAKER: Yep.

00:07:59.890 --> 00:08:01.210
HUGH ACHESON: So,
diamond crystal

00:08:01.210 --> 00:08:02.610
is the one we all use
in restaurants, it just

00:08:02.610 --> 00:08:03.560
feels right.

00:08:03.560 --> 00:08:06.630
It's dorky, but if you use
another type-- and salt differs

00:08:06.630 --> 00:08:08.980
a lot, if you take
Morton's kosher salt,

00:08:08.980 --> 00:08:12.570
and weigh the amount that
it takes to be a gram,

00:08:12.570 --> 00:08:14.880
is far different
from diamond crystal.

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:19.629
So it just helps to get
a solid reference point.

00:08:19.629 --> 00:08:21.420
So the fresh thyme is
going to go in there,

00:08:21.420 --> 00:08:23.520
and then I'm going to slather
them with a lot of olive oil.

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:25.478
The thyme's really just
going to flavor it out,

00:08:25.478 --> 00:08:27.990
so I want to beat it up as
I'm sticking it in there.

00:08:27.990 --> 00:08:31.145
I'm looking over at these,
and they're not burning,

00:08:31.145 --> 00:08:33.145
they're doing what they're
supposed to be doing.

00:08:33.145 --> 00:08:35.260
And anyhow, in the modern
school of cheffery,

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:37.470
burning stuff is cool.

00:08:37.470 --> 00:08:39.780
So it's like,
everything's charred now.

00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:44.030
It's like, wow, who
got really lazy?

00:08:44.030 --> 00:08:46.450
I'm going to put a lot of
olive oil over the top of them.

00:08:46.450 --> 00:08:49.260
That's just going to
give it a lot of flavor.

00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:52.999
And I'm going to bring that up--
going to bring the pan up hot.

00:08:52.999 --> 00:08:55.540
Normally you could just take it
a pan that's room temperature

00:08:55.540 --> 00:08:56.860
and get them in the oven.

00:08:56.860 --> 00:08:58.740
I'm just aiding
this because it's

00:08:58.740 --> 00:09:01.690
a longer process than the
30 hours of quality time

00:09:01.690 --> 00:09:04.410
we have together.

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:06.780
Into the oven we go.

00:09:06.780 --> 00:09:10.640
And let's go back--
what are you doing?

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:13.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:13.240 --> 00:09:14.630
HUGH ACHESON: OK.

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:19.970
Nobody saw that Hugh,
everything's fine.

00:09:19.970 --> 00:09:21.160
I'm going to check on these.

00:09:21.160 --> 00:09:22.910
They're doing what
they're supposed to do.

00:09:22.910 --> 00:09:25.800
Now did you notice the one
of things I'm not doing

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:29.840
is-- cooking is a matter of
paying attention to the stove,

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:33.910
but you do not have to be
doing this all the time.

00:09:33.910 --> 00:09:36.930
I don't know why, my wife
is always like-- I'm, like,

00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:38.060
what you're doing?

00:09:38.060 --> 00:09:38.884
So just let it go.

00:09:38.884 --> 00:09:40.550
It's caramelizing,
it's doing its thing,

00:09:40.550 --> 00:09:44.400
just let it mellow
out and enjoy the time

00:09:44.400 --> 00:09:45.880
you're having with your onions.

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:47.861
I just turned it down to five.

00:09:47.861 --> 00:09:49.860
If you don't have a numeric
system on your stove

00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:52.282
you are not going to
learn anything today.

00:09:52.282 --> 00:09:53.740
So on top of all
this, you're going

00:09:53.740 --> 00:09:54.901
to have to buy a new stove.

00:09:54.901 --> 00:09:57.275
This is going to be a really
expensive free demonstration

00:09:57.275 --> 00:09:58.510
and a $10 book.

00:09:58.510 --> 00:10:02.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:02.020 --> 00:10:03.980
HUGH ACHESON: This is a melon.

00:10:03.980 --> 00:10:06.840
It is a cantaloupe.

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:10.740
It's season is just beginning,
if we were in south Georgia,

00:10:10.740 --> 00:10:13.000
north Florida we would
see them right now.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:14.860
I'm just going to cut down.

00:10:14.860 --> 00:10:17.624
And any fruit, if you're
making orange supremes,

00:10:17.624 --> 00:10:19.040
it's the same
thing, you're trying

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:20.760
to create a flat
surface by cutting off

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:21.794
the top and the bottom.

00:10:21.794 --> 00:10:23.210
And then you're
going around on it

00:10:23.210 --> 00:10:25.770
pretending like
you're cutting off

00:10:25.770 --> 00:10:29.030
the outer layer of the globe.

00:10:29.030 --> 00:10:30.990
Civilization is
doing that by itself,

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:38.310
but we're going to do this
well-- So all the way down,

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:40.350
and I'm going to circle
around, sometimes

00:10:40.350 --> 00:10:43.530
you miss a little nubbin on
the bottom, but I nailed it.

00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:47.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:47.690 --> 00:10:51.110
HUGH ACHESON: Down--
I'm not, yeah I am.

00:10:51.110 --> 00:10:57.770
Then I'm going to scoop out the
center seeds, just carefully

00:10:57.770 --> 00:11:00.810
and that's about it.

00:11:00.810 --> 00:11:03.670
So let's talk about
convenience items in stores

00:11:03.670 --> 00:11:06.880
and what you're doing wrong.

00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:10.782
If you go and buy
cubed cantaloupe

00:11:10.782 --> 00:11:12.740
you're paying somebody
to do a lot of the work,

00:11:12.740 --> 00:11:14.140
you understand that, right?

00:11:14.140 --> 00:11:15.640
And I'm not saying
your time is not

00:11:15.640 --> 00:11:17.790
more important than
cubing cantaloupe,

00:11:17.790 --> 00:11:22.760
but if you buy crumbled
feta, what is wrong with you?

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:24.455
Have you ever tried
to crumble feta?

00:11:24.455 --> 00:11:27.360
It is not very challenging.

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:30.910
Like it just literally
crumbles within your fingers.

00:11:30.910 --> 00:11:33.210
Yet, it is a commodity product.

00:11:33.210 --> 00:11:35.090
That is amazing to me.

00:11:35.090 --> 00:11:36.809
I'm going to cut
some slices of this.

00:11:36.809 --> 00:11:38.350
You guys are like,
this guy is weird.

00:11:38.350 --> 00:11:41.090
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:41.090 --> 00:11:42.322
AUDIENCE: First question.

00:11:42.322 --> 00:11:43.530
HUGH ACHESON: First question.

00:11:43.530 --> 00:11:46.384
AUDIENCE: How do you
identify a ripe cantaloupe?

00:11:46.384 --> 00:11:48.300
HUGH ACHESON: Smell it,
aromatically it should

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:49.260
it smell ripe.

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:53.210
It shouldn't be soft at all, but
it should have firmness to it,

00:11:53.210 --> 00:11:54.890
but not be rock solid.

00:11:54.890 --> 00:11:57.860
If you hear sloshing inside,
it means that it's probably

00:11:57.860 --> 00:12:01.350
weirdly ripe inside.

00:12:01.350 --> 00:12:05.950
So trust your gut, or you
find, like Curtis Stone

00:12:05.950 --> 00:12:06.980
in a grocery store.

00:12:06.980 --> 00:12:08.090
Do you remember
that show he used

00:12:08.090 --> 00:12:10.530
