Don't throw these away
because either they're

00:20:21.321 --> 00:20:22.820
going to go into
your chicken stock,

00:20:22.820 --> 00:20:25.028
or you're going to dutifully
mince them and make them

00:20:25.028 --> 00:20:27.070
into a pickled chow chow.

00:20:27.070 --> 00:20:30.480
But y'all are busy, so maybe
just the stock, or hell.

00:20:30.480 --> 00:20:31.400
The compost pile.

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:34.770
I don't know, whatever you want
to do, you're in your kitchen,

00:20:34.770 --> 00:20:37.600
I'm not following you
home, like Curtis Stone

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:38.590
in that creepy show.

00:20:38.590 --> 00:20:39.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:39.800 --> 00:20:41.370
So I'm clipping
the end off where

00:20:41.370 --> 00:20:48.250
its root was attached to
it, and it was in the soil.

00:20:48.250 --> 00:20:53.030
And then if we see here,
this is the core part

00:20:53.030 --> 00:20:55.700
that is a little
firmer, so I'm just

00:20:55.700 --> 00:21:00.420
going to make a little v cut on
that, and cut off some of that.

00:21:00.420 --> 00:21:04.490
Leaving still enough of it--
it's just like the onion,

00:21:04.490 --> 00:21:06.390
to hold it together.

00:21:06.390 --> 00:21:12.240
Then we're going
to take a Benriner,

00:21:12.240 --> 00:21:16.240
a lot of you guys work with
your fingers and typing,

00:21:16.240 --> 00:21:20.560
so you don't-- You could use
a knife for this if you want,

00:21:20.560 --> 00:21:23.080
but this is a
Japanese mandoline,

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:24.940
and they're really
ballistically sharp.

00:21:27.890 --> 00:21:32.650
They probably account for
more cuts in the kitchen

00:21:32.650 --> 00:21:34.762
than pretty much anything.

00:21:34.762 --> 00:21:36.220
And what we're
doing is, we're just

00:21:36.220 --> 00:21:41.580
going to slice it pretty thinly.

