But, you know, to me it's
like two big rib-eyes

00:34:14.429 --> 00:34:15.949
for the four of
us, that probably

00:34:15.949 --> 00:34:19.139
amount to four ounces
of meat per person.

00:34:19.139 --> 00:34:20.909
And I cook them on
this little tiny--

00:34:20.909 --> 00:34:23.090
I've got this-- what's
called a-- what's it called?

00:34:23.090 --> 00:34:26.704
A lodge, like
outdoors-man grill,

00:34:26.704 --> 00:34:28.620
but it's just like this
little tiny cast iron,

00:34:28.620 --> 00:34:31.270
all cast iron grill,
that is awesomely cool,

00:34:31.270 --> 00:34:33.400
and fun, and inexpensive.

00:34:33.400 --> 00:34:36.320
But then next to it is
three different salads

00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:39.739
like this, and wheat berries,
or they're big fans of farro.

00:34:39.739 --> 00:34:44.840
And it's just a spread, and
oftentimes we eat family style,

00:34:44.840 --> 00:34:47.214
so I'll just line up
six platters of stuff

00:34:47.214 --> 00:34:48.880
and we'll have-- sit
around the counter,

00:34:48.880 --> 00:34:50.255
and we'll have
four empty plates,

00:34:50.255 --> 00:34:52.330
and we'll just plate it up.

00:34:52.330 --> 00:34:56.130
As a parent I've found
that kids eat really well,

00:34:56.130 --> 00:34:58.000
this is going to put
a lot of light bulbs

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:00.860
above peoples heads,
but when they're hungry.

00:35:00.860 --> 00:35:05.650
So if they have a 5:30 snack,
and you're eating at 6:30,

00:35:05.650 --> 00:35:07.290
they're probably
not really hungry,

00:35:07.290 --> 00:35:10.160
and that's when you see the
vegetable pushing game off

00:35:10.160 --> 00:35:11.310
to the sides.

00:35:11.310 --> 00:35:15.170
So you got to make them
hungry, so don't feed them.

00:35:15.170 --> 00:35:17.885
Now, I mean, just don't feed
them a bunch of crap at 5:30

00:35:17.885 --> 00:35:19.260
and you're going
to have a better

00:35:19.260 --> 00:35:20.880
chance of feeding them well.

00:35:20.880 --> 00:35:21.820
But they eat anything.

00:35:21.820 --> 00:35:24.140
If I roast them a chicken,
and Carolina gold rice,

00:35:24.140 --> 00:35:27.490
and old school country
gravy, and then next to that

00:35:27.490 --> 00:35:31.950
is escarole, and beets, and
roasted carrots, and peas,

00:35:31.950 --> 00:35:33.400
they'll eat all of that.

00:35:33.400 --> 00:35:36.820
Which is good, which is
good, they're healthy kids.

00:35:36.820 --> 00:35:39.100
AUDIENCE: So besides
de-worming tweezers,

00:35:39.100 --> 00:35:41.525
what is your favorite
kitchen instrument and why?

00:35:45.400 --> 00:35:46.940
HUGH ACHESON: Probably spoons.

00:35:46.940 --> 00:35:52.040
I mean, I know it sounds
dorky, but we use spoons a lot.

00:35:52.040 --> 00:35:55.986
But we use them as spatulas, we
use them as everything a lot.

00:35:55.986 --> 00:35:57.610
They're versatile,
but these are bigger

00:35:57.610 --> 00:36:01.470
than your standard spoons--
this one's also slotted.

00:36:01.470 --> 00:36:03.777
They're called
Kunz spoons, but it

00:36:03.777 --> 00:36:05.610
was designed by a guy
named Gary Kunz, who's

00:36:05.610 --> 00:36:06.930
a really famous
chef in New York.

00:36:06.930 --> 00:36:08.700
He was the chef at
Lespinasse at one time.

00:36:08.700 --> 00:36:10.830
But, whatever.

00:36:10.830 --> 00:36:13.307
And I like a Vitamix blender.

00:36:13.307 --> 00:36:14.890
They're just really
powerful blenders.

00:36:14.890 --> 00:36:17.180
They're really handy for making
smoothies in the morning,

00:36:17.180 --> 00:36:19.388
and making vinaigrettes,
they make soups, and purees,

00:36:19.388 --> 00:36:21.080
and all that sort of stuff.

00:36:21.080 --> 00:36:22.690
So, they're good.

00:36:22.690 --> 00:36:24.770
I think investing in
good pans is good.

00:36:24.770 --> 00:36:26.350
But you don't necessarily
have to spend a lot of money,

00:36:26.350 --> 00:36:28.433
if you don't want to spend
a lot of money on pans.

00:36:28.433 --> 00:36:30.520
Buy cast iron, but you
have to take care of it.

00:36:30.520 --> 00:36:33.700
And you have to watch a YouTube
tutorial, which one of you

00:36:33.700 --> 00:36:35.730
probably has edited
somewhere along the line,

00:36:35.730 --> 00:36:38.620
on taking care and
refinishing cast iron pans,

00:36:38.620 --> 00:36:41.120
because it's a lot different
than what your grandmother told

00:36:41.120 --> 00:36:41.620
you.

00:36:41.620 --> 00:36:44.320
She was generally wrong.

