00:37:03.940 --> 00:37:04.796
and grits.

00:37:04.796 --> 00:37:07.295
Which you could do polenta or
whatever instead of the grits,

00:37:07.295 --> 00:37:08.970
if you can't find them out here.

00:37:08.970 --> 00:37:11.780
That's great and really simple,
and really straightforward,

00:37:11.780 --> 00:37:13.900
that resonates with
spring, it also

00:37:13.900 --> 00:37:15.470
resonates with--
you guys probably

00:37:15.470 --> 00:37:17.270
don't have much time
off, but maybe you

00:37:17.270 --> 00:37:20.130
could do that on Sunday
morning, so Yeah.

00:37:20.130 --> 00:37:21.540
I'm thinking about you.

00:37:21.540 --> 00:37:24.160
AUDIENCE: What's your go to
anchovy brand these days?

00:37:24.160 --> 00:37:27.750
HUGH ACHESON: Go to anchovy
brand, hum, I don't know.

00:37:27.750 --> 00:37:31.610
We buy really-- large
things, we cure our own too,

00:37:31.610 --> 00:37:33.000
so I don't know.

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:37.010
I mean, I've had great success
with buying Spanish products

00:37:37.010 --> 00:37:38.220
on Amazon.

00:37:38.220 --> 00:37:40.702
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:40.702 --> 00:37:42.660
HUGH ACHESON: I mean I
live in Athens, Georgia,

00:37:42.660 --> 00:37:44.120
I don't have many options.

00:37:44.120 --> 00:37:46.160
But I get a lot of
[INAUDIBLE] canned tuna

00:37:46.160 --> 00:37:48.240
and stuff like that,
I find it cheapest

00:37:48.240 --> 00:37:51.120
there, so try one of those.

00:37:51.120 --> 00:37:54.370
I mean look for Delician brand.

00:37:54.370 --> 00:37:56.110
One of those ones,
would be good.

00:37:56.110 --> 00:37:58.429
AUDIENCE: Your first book
won a James Beard award.

00:37:58.429 --> 00:37:59.220
HUGH ACHESON: Yeah.

00:37:59.220 --> 00:38:00.830
AUDIENCE: And I'm
wondering about the role

00:38:00.830 --> 00:38:01.830
of writing in your life.

00:38:01.830 --> 00:38:04.246
I know you said earlier that
you do quite a bit of writing

00:38:04.246 --> 00:38:08.440
and if this creative pursuit
and that one sort of mesh

00:38:08.440 --> 00:38:09.960
together and--

00:38:09.960 --> 00:38:12.570
HUGH ACHESON: I
think they do, yeah.

00:38:12.570 --> 00:38:15.550
I never really-- somebody was
like, you should do a cookbook,

00:38:15.550 --> 00:38:16.959
and I was like OK.

00:38:16.959 --> 00:38:19.500
I was like, man, that will be
easy, I've got all the recipes,

00:38:19.500 --> 00:38:21.320
and then you have nothing.

00:38:21.320 --> 00:38:22.210
You really don't.

00:38:22.210 --> 00:38:25.090
I mean I've got-- I have systems
of telling people what to do

00:38:25.090 --> 00:38:28.420
and basic recipes
for restaurants.

00:38:28.420 --> 00:38:30.290
I don't have anything
for home cooks.

00:38:30.290 --> 00:38:32.830
So when you're writing
for a home cook,

00:38:32.830 --> 00:38:34.869
literally I get
emails saying, you

00:38:34.869 --> 00:38:36.910
know it said crack four
eggs, and used four eggs,

00:38:36.910 --> 00:38:38.743
but you didn't tell me
to remove the shells.

00:38:38.743 --> 00:38:40.244
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:40.244 --> 00:38:41.660
HUGH ACHESON: So
it's not like I'm

00:38:41.660 --> 00:38:44.330
saying I have to be
instructing people

00:38:44.330 --> 00:38:49.070
that know absolutely nothing,
but it's very wide spectrum.

00:38:49.070 --> 00:38:51.800
But I like writing, I'm
not very good at it.

00:38:51.800 --> 00:38:53.100
I dropped out of college.

00:38:53.100 --> 00:38:56.630
I come from a really
super academic family,

00:38:56.630 --> 00:38:59.360
and I was the black sheep.

00:38:59.360 --> 00:39:01.915
But I like it, and
it sort of tests me

00:39:01.915 --> 00:39:04.660
and drives me to do it more.

00:39:04.660 --> 00:39:07.750
And I think the only way you get
good at writing is by writing.

00:39:07.750 --> 00:39:11.070
And you write and write
and rewrite and write,

00:39:11.070 --> 00:39:12.390
and you just have to do it.

00:39:12.390 --> 00:39:14.920
So you tell stories,
and narrative,

00:39:14.920 --> 00:39:17.740
and anecdotes about
food in an attempt

00:39:17.740 --> 00:39:19.360
to get people to
fully understand what

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:20.580
you're trying to get across.

00:39:20.580 --> 00:39:23.260
The how to on recipes is
the most difficult thing.

00:39:23.260 --> 00:39:24.247
It can be easy.

00:39:24.247 --> 00:39:26.580
But if it's easy it usually
doesn't really fully explain

00:39:26.580 --> 00:39:28.300
what you're having somebody do.

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:30.450
And it's really hard.

00:39:30.450 --> 00:39:33.330
If every cookbook was animated,
with a little animated

00:39:33.330 --> 00:39:36.500
button off to the side, that
would be great, but it's not.

00:39:40.950 --> 00:39:42.800
Hold on.

00:39:42.800 --> 00:39:47.302
Google is not on fire,
there's just a little--

00:39:47.302 --> 00:39:50.200
FEMALE SPEAKER:
We've got one more.

00:39:50.200 --> 00:39:52.820
AUDIENCE: I have an issue
where vegetables go bad.

00:39:52.820 --> 00:39:54.660
Like I'll buy a ton at once.

00:39:54.660 --> 00:39:59.760
What are good staple veggies or
the most versatile vegetables

00:39:59.760 --> 00:40:00.390
to have.

00:40:00.390 --> 00:40:01.306
HUGH ACHESON: Carrots.

00:40:03.820 --> 00:40:05.390
People buy a lot
more than they need,

00:40:05.390 --> 00:40:09.290
but buying really small amounts
is crazy stupid expensive

00:40:09.290 --> 00:40:10.102
sometimes.

00:40:10.102 --> 00:40:11.810
Now there's those
groups like Blue Apron,

00:40:11.810 --> 00:40:13.750
and all these little
prep companies that

00:40:13.750 --> 00:40:16.819
deliver you a stupid
prepped-- and I

00:40:16.819 --> 00:40:19.235
don't want you to do that,
it's just silly and overpriced,

00:40:19.235 --> 00:40:22.973
but, if one of your spouses
owns that company, I'm sorry.

00:40:25.690 --> 00:40:27.482
I think that staples
in my fridge,

00:40:27.482 --> 00:40:29.190
that aren't going to
go bad very quickly,

00:40:29.190 --> 00:40:33.160
are going to be carrots,
onions, celery, obviously, these

00:40:33.160 --> 00:40:37.624
are main core of a lot of
French cooking, fennel.

00:40:37.624 --> 00:40:39.790
I usually always have button
mushrooms, or something

00:40:39.790 --> 00:40:41.914
as simple button mushrooms,
and then the rest of it

00:40:41.914 --> 00:40:45.150
is from the market-- and from
the farmer's market on Saturday

00:40:45.150 --> 00:40:46.110
I buy some things.

00:40:46.110 --> 00:40:47.930
How you store it is
really important.

00:40:47.930 --> 00:40:50.520
Ziploc bags with a
moist paper towel

00:40:50.520 --> 00:40:53.210
inside is going to keep
lettuces a lot longer, arugula

00:40:53.210 --> 00:40:56.140
a lot longer, than just
standard shoving them

00:40:56.140 --> 00:40:57.734
in the regular part fridge.

00:40:57.734 --> 00:40:59.400
The crisper drawer
is there for a reason

00:40:59.400 --> 00:41:02.350
though, it's kind of a
humidity controlled area.

00:41:02.350 --> 00:41:06.800
And will keep things from
drying out more than anything.

00:41:06.800 --> 00:41:10.286
So I'm trying to think
what other vegetables.

00:41:10.286 --> 00:41:11.660
I mean obviously,
root vegetables

00:41:11.660 --> 00:41:15.110
are going to have a
long time to them.

00:41:15.110 --> 00:41:17.480
Any leafy frilly stuff
you just have to use.

00:41:17.480 --> 00:41:20.320
But that's the other thing,
if you buy something,

00:41:20.320 --> 00:41:22.950
it's the way we
consume anything,

00:41:22.950 --> 00:41:26.380
if you don't have a real
purpose for it, don't buy it.

00:41:26.380 --> 00:41:28.380
You need to be thinking
about what you're doing.

00:41:28.380 --> 00:41:30.129
But that's the challenge
of the CSA boxes,

00:41:30.129 --> 00:41:32.960
that you get the stuff and
you don't have a choice.

00:41:32.960 --> 00:41:35.242
So you better love lettuce.

00:41:35.242 --> 00:41:36.950
AUDIENCE: I heard
through the rumor mill,

00:41:36.950 --> 00:41:38.470
actually I read
an online article,

00:41:38.470 --> 00:41:40.849
that you're opening a coffee
bar in Ponce City Market--

00:41:40.849 --> 00:41:41.640
HUGH ACHESON: I am.

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:42.400
AUDIENCE: which is super cool.

00:41:42.400 --> 00:41:44.192
So I was just wondering
what drove you to--

00:41:44.192 --> 00:41:46.025
HUGH ACHESON: I heard
through the rumor mill

00:41:46.025 --> 00:41:48.510
that you guys are opening up
an office there, is that true?

00:41:48.510 --> 00:41:50.810
AUDIENCE: Maybe, maybe not.

00:41:50.810 --> 00:41:51.895
Unconfirmed.

00:41:51.895 --> 00:41:53.290
HUGH ACHESON: Unconfirmed.

00:41:53.290 --> 00:41:55.040
AUDIENCE: But I'd love
to hear about that.

00:41:55.040 --> 00:41:59.059
HUGH ACHESON: So, I guess
when I opened up Empire State

00:41:59.059 --> 00:42:01.100
South, which is a real
big restaurant in Atlanta,

00:42:01.100 --> 00:42:03.770
I was like, man, a lot of
people are doing restaurants.

00:42:03.770 --> 00:42:06.874
This was five years ago and
mixology was becoming the thing

00:42:06.874 --> 00:42:08.540
again and whatever,
but I kept thinking,

00:42:08.540 --> 00:42:09.540
you know a lot of
people aren't really

00:42:09.540 --> 00:42:11.210
doing the bookends of a meal.

00:42:11.210 --> 00:42:12.670
They're not really
paying attention

00:42:12.670 --> 00:42:15.310
to great beverage program at
the beginning of your meal,

00:42:15.310 --> 00:42:17.101
when you sit down
before you get food,

00:42:17.101 --> 00:42:19.350
and then they're definitely
not thinking about coffee,

00:42:19.350 --> 00:42:21.516
because they don't care
about coffee, because coffee

00:42:21.516 --> 00:42:22.910
doesn't make them any money.

00:42:22.910 --> 00:42:25.820
So I was like, well,
I care about coffee,

00:42:25.820 --> 00:42:27.010
because I love coffee.

00:42:27.010 --> 00:42:30.370
And I was like, what if we
did a really elaborate, really

00:42:30.370 --> 00:42:31.830
good coffee program.

00:42:31.830 --> 00:42:34.430
So we put one in Empire, and
it was a really big success.

00:42:34.430 --> 00:42:38.230
It probably doesn't make
that much money still,

00:42:38.230 --> 00:42:42.250
but it's been worth it and
it's gathered a lot of acclaim.

00:42:42.250 --> 00:42:45.460
I have one guy there
named Dale Donchey.

00:42:45.460 --> 00:42:50.780
And Dale's in this wonderful
world of third rail coffee,

00:42:50.780 --> 00:42:53.760
and third rail restaurants,
and all this DIY culture.

00:42:53.760 --> 00:42:56.580
It's just a lot of people
nerding out on single topics,

00:42:56.580 --> 00:42:59.020
and Dale's just this
classic coffee nerd,

00:42:59.020 --> 00:43:01.920
and he just knows
a ton about coffee.

00:43:01.920 --> 00:43:02.830
And he's a great guy.

00:43:02.830 --> 00:43:04.130
He's a really good leader.

00:43:04.130 --> 00:43:06.400
So he and I are
starting a restaurant,

00:43:06.400 --> 00:43:08.904
which is a massive kiosk.

00:43:08.904 --> 00:43:10.570
I'm trying to think
what else wa-- oh, I

00:43:10.570 --> 00:43:14.030
went to-- what was that
coffee shop I was at

00:43:14.030 --> 00:43:15.480
in LA-- Sightglass.

00:43:15.480 --> 00:43:16.935
FEMALE SPEAKER: Sightglass.

00:43:16.935 --> 00:43:18.685
HUGH ACHESON: Sightglass.
--the other day.

00:43:18.685 --> 00:43:20.950
It's kind of like that set
up, but if I didn't own

00:43:20.950 --> 00:43:23.222
everything else in the room.

00:43:23.222 --> 00:43:25.680
So it's just an island, and
it's called Spiller Park, which

00:43:25.680 --> 00:43:29.260
is the old name of the Atlanta
Crackers Baseball Team Stadium

00:43:29.260 --> 00:43:32.420
that was on the site of
where Ponce City Market is.

00:43:32.420 --> 00:43:37.242
So it'll be open-- it's a
multi roaster company, until we

00:43:37.242 --> 00:43:38.700
start roasting our
own beans, which

00:43:38.700 --> 00:43:41.000
is about a year and a half.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:44.800
So we'll be using Four Barrel,
and there's roasters out here

00:43:44.800 --> 00:43:47.470
we love, but there are a lot
of Canadian roasters we love.

00:43:47.470 --> 00:43:51.000
Who's a coffee nerd
in here, anybody?

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:53.460
49th parallel, which
is great, which

00:43:53.460 --> 00:43:56.740
is from Vancouver, Phil
and Sebastian from Calgary,

00:43:56.740 --> 00:44:01.156
Four Barrel Heart from Portland,
couple others, George Howell.

00:44:01.156 --> 00:44:02.290
So, yeah, we're excited.

00:44:02.290 --> 00:44:03.770
That'll be open in--

00:44:03.770 --> 00:44:06.020
So Ponce City Market, is
the second largest brick

00:44:06.020 --> 00:44:08.640
edifice in North America, and
it's the old Atlanta City Hall

00:44:08.640 --> 00:44:10.790
East, and before that was
the Sears distribution

00:44:10.790 --> 00:44:11.770
center in Atlanta.

00:44:11.770 --> 00:44:15.970
It's this amazingly massive
building, that's very complex

00:44:15.970 --> 00:44:18.210
and a lot of tech
companies and other stuff

00:44:18.210 --> 00:44:19.960
are moving in there,
MailChimp's in there,

00:44:19.960 --> 00:44:21.668
a bunch of other
groups, but then there's

00:44:21.668 --> 00:44:25.680
an elaborate retail level
with anthropology and crap

00:44:25.680 --> 00:44:26.880
like that.

00:44:26.880 --> 00:44:28.970
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank
you so much for coming.

